date=December 13, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! colspan=9|Overall reference for name, dates, duration, winds and pressure:{{EPAC hurricane best track}}\n|}\n\n==Landfalls==\n{{bar chart|float=right\n| title = [[Landfall (meteorology)|Landfalls]] by month<ref name=\"EPAC HURDAT\"/>\n| data_max = 8\n| label_type = Month\n| data_type = Number of storms\n| label1 = July\n| data1 = 2\n| label2 = August\n| data2 = 4\n| label3 = September\n| data3 = 4\n| label4 = October\n| data4 = 8\n}}\nOf the 82 Category&nbsp;3 hurricanes in the east and central Pacific, a total of 14&nbsp;made [[landfall]] while still a tropical cyclone, collectively resulting in 18&nbsp;landfalls.<ref name=\"EPAC HURDAT\"/> As tropical cyclones approach land, they tend to weaken due to land interaction, cooler waters, shallower waters due to [[Continental shelf|shelving]], increased [[vertical wind shear]], or dry air.<ref>{{cite report |author1=Richard D. Knabb |author2=Jamie R. Rhome |author3=Daniel P. Brown |date=December 20, 2005 |title=Tropical Cyclone Report: Hurricane Katrina |url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/data/tcr/AL122005_Katrina.pdf |publisher=National Hurricane Center |pages=3\u20134 |access-date=July 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180609062326/https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/data/tcr/AL122005_Katrina.pdf |archivedate=2018-06-09 |url-status=live }}</ref> As such, only four of these 14&nbsp;hurricanes have made landfall while still at Category&nbsp;3 intensity: Olivia of 1967, Olivia of 1975, Kiko of 1989, and Lane of 2006. Only three made more than one landfall during their lifespan: Hilary of 1993, which made three landfalls, as well as Olivia of 1967 and Fausto of 1996, which made two landfalls each. Only two years&nbsp;\u2013 1971 and 1984&nbsp;\u2013 saw more than one Category&nbsp;3 hurricane make landfall, though in neither year any of those Category&nbsp;3 hurricanes made landfall as hurricanes.<ref name=\"EPAC HURDAT\"/> In the following table, dates where storms made landfall are listed next to the landfall locations.{{#tag:ref||name=\"UTC\"|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=\"100%\"\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"10%\" |Name\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"5%\" |Year\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"16%\" style=\"background: #{{storm colour|cat3}};\" |Category&nbsp;3\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"16%\" style=\"background: #{{storm colour|cat2}};\" |Category&nbsp;2\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"16%\" style=\"background: #{{storm colour|cat1}};\" |Category&nbsp;1\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"16%\" style=\"background: #{{storm colour|storm}};\" |Tropical&nbsp;storm\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"16%\" style=\"background: #{{storm colour|depression}};\" |Tropical&nbsp;depression\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"5%\" class=\"unsortable\"|{{abbr|Refs|References}}\n|-\n| [[1967 Pacific hurricane season#Hurricane Olivia|Olivia]] || 1967 || [[Baja California Sur]] (October&nbsp;14) || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || [[Baja California Sur]] (October&nbsp;13) || &nbsp;\u2014 || <ref name=\"1967sum\"/>\n|-\n| [[Hurricane Irene\u2013Olivia|Olivia]] || 1971 || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || [[Baja California Sur]] (September&nbsp;30) || <ref name=\"1971MWR\"/>\n|-\n| [[1971 Pacific hurricane season#Hurricane Priscilla|Priscilla]] || 1971 || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || [[Nayarit]] (October&nbsp;12) || &nbsp;\u2014 || <ref name=\"1971MWR\"/>\n|-\n| [[Hurricane Olivia (1975)|Olivia]] || 1975 || [[Sinaloa]] (October&nbsp;25) || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || <ref name=\"1975MWR\"/>\n|-\n| [[Hurricane Norma (1981)|Norma]] || 1981 || &nbsp;\u2014 || [[Sinaloa]] (October&nbsp;12) || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || <ref name=\"1981MWR\"/>\n|-\n| [[1984 Pacific hurricane season#Hurricane Genevieve|Genevieve]] || 1984 || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || [[Baja California Sur]] (July&nbsp;14) || <ref name=\"1984MWR\">{{cite journal|first1=Emil B|last1=Gunther|first2=Robert L|last2=Cross|title=Eastern North Pacific Tropical Cyclones of 1984|journal=Monthly Weather Review|date=August 1985|volume=113|issue=8|pages=1393\u20131410|doi=10.1175/1520-0493(1985)113<1393:ENPTCO>2.0.CO;2|issn=1520-0493|bibcode=1985MWRv..113.1393G}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[1984 Pacific hurricane season#Hurricane Polo|Polo]] || 1984 || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || [[Baja California Sur]] (October&nbsp;3) || <ref name=\"1984MWR\"/>\n|-\n| [[Hurricane Kiko (1989)|Kiko]] || 1989 || [[Baja California Sur]] (August&nbsp;27) || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || <ref name=\"Kiko1989PTCR\"/>\n|-\n| [[Hurricane Winifred (1992)|Winifred]] || 1992 || &nbsp;\u2014 || [[Colima]] (October&nbsp;9) || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || <ref name=\"Winifred1992PTCR\"/>\n|-\n| [[Hurricane Hilary (1993)|Hilary]] || 1993 || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || [[Baja California Sur]] (\u00d72, both on August&nbsp;25) || [[Sonora]] (August&nbsp;26) || <ref name=\"Hilary1993PTCR\"/>\n|-\n| [[Hurricane Fausto (1996)|Fausto]] || 1996 || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || [[Baja California Sur]] (September&nbsp;13), [[Sinaloa]] (September&nbsp;14) || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || <ref name=\"Fausto1996PTCR\"/>\n|-\n| [[Hurricane Lane (2006)|Lane]] || 2006 || [[Sinaloa]] (September&nbsp;16) || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || <ref name=\"Lane2006TCR\"/>\n|-\n| [[Hurricane Jova (2011)|Jova]] || 2011 || &nbsp;\u2014 || [[Jalisco]] (October&nbsp;12) || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || <ref name=\"Jova2011TCR\"/>\n|-\n| [[Hurricane Darby (2016)|Darby]] || 2016 || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || &nbsp;\u2014 || [[Big Island, Hawaii]] (July&nbsp;24) || &nbsp;\u2014 || <ref name=\"Darby2016TCR\"/>\n|-\n!colspan=\"8\" |Overall reference for landfall intensity:<ref name=\"EPAC HURDAT\"/>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Tropical cyclones|Weather}}\n* [[List of Pacific hurricanes]]\n* [[List of Pacific hurricane seasons]]\n* Pacific hurricanes by intensity:\n** [[List of Eastern Pacific tropical storms]]\n** [[List of Category 1 Pacific hurricanes]]\n** [[List of Category 2 Pacific hurricanes]]\n** [[List of Category 4 Pacific hurricanes]]\n** [[List of Category 5 Pacific hurricanes]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{Eastern Pacific tropical cyclones}}\n{{Category 3 Pacific hurricanes}}\n{{featured list}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List of Category 3 Pacific hurricanes}}\n[[Category:Category 3 Pacific hurricanes|List]]\n[[Category:Lists of tropical cyclones|Category 3 Pacific hurricanes]]\n[[Category:Tropical cyclone intensity articles]]\n", "name_user": "KN2731", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLandfalls:here too", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Category_3_Pacific_hurricanes"}
{"title_page": "Julio Aguilera", "text_new": "[[Image:Julio Aguilera by Vicente Saavedra.jpg|220px|right|thumb|''Julio Aguilera'' by Venezuelan painter [[Vicente Saavedra]]]][[Image:Julio Aguilera.jpg|220px|right|thumb|Julio Aguilera during his still hairy Kung Fu days.]][[Image:War and Peace - Julio Aguilera.jpg|220px|right|thumb|''War and Peace''. Bronze, 2004]]'''Julio C\u00e9sar Aguilera Pe\u00f1a''' is a Venezuelan-American painter and sculptor born in [[Caracas]], on July 28, 1961. Previously to his career as an artist, Aguilera was awarded the sixth [[dan rank#Modern usage in China|Dan]] in [[Kung Fu]] when he was just 26 years old.<ref name=\"certificado\">{{cite web|title=La Venciclopedia |work=Certificado de Julio Aguilera |url=https://www.venciclopedia.org/index.php?title=Categor%C3%ADa:Im%C3%A1genes_de_Julio_Aguilera#/media/File:Certificado_Julio_Aguilera.jpg |accessdate=August 3, 2019 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nAguilera was born in [[Catia, Caracas|Catia]], one of the poor neighborhoods surrounding [[Caracas]]. His mother died at birth and he was raised by his grandmother and other relatives. At age 6, he was making a living as a shoe polisher while attending primary school. After graduating from high school in 1978 from the Colegio San Agustin, Julio studied at the [[Universidad Pedag\u00f3gica Experimental Libertador|Instituto Pedag\u00f3gico de Caracas]].\n\nAguilera was inclined towards the arts since he was in primary school, and he began painting at a young age after a local painter gave him a handful of used brushes and half-empty tubes of oil paint.<ref>[http://www.artareas.com/ArtAreas/home.nsf/Profiles/JULIO+AGUILERA Julio Aguilera: A Venezuelan Artist Makes His Mark in North America] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070410224514/http://artareas.com/ArtAreas/home.nsf/Profiles/JULIO+AGUILERA |date=2007-04-10 }} Ed McCormack. Gallery & Studio, March, 2005</ref> However strong, his artistic inclinations had to take a back seat for several years while Aguilera struggled to move out of the slums. During this time, he painted mostly for enjoyment, giving away his canvases to friends and relatives while he made his way through school. While at the ''Instituto Pedag\u00f3gico'', Julio enrolled himself in the academy of [[Chan Lee Kam Fai]], one of Venezuela's most renowned martial arts training academies.,<ref name=\"Cham Kam Fai\">{{cite web|title=Hung Sing Choy Lee Fut |work=Maestro Cham Kam Fai |url=http://taichi.cl//index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=14&Itemid=27 |accessdate=September 13, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070822201646/http://www.taichi.cl/ |archivedate=August 22, 2007 }}</ref> unbeknownst Julio, he would later become the future president of the Venezuelan Federation of Chinese Martial Arts and the International Hung Sing Choy Li Fat Chan Kim Fay.<ref name=\"Cham Kam Fai 2\">{{cite web | title=Choy Li Fat Venezuela | work=Historia del estilo Choy Li Fat(C) y Cai Li Fo(M) | url= http://www.angelfire.com/planet/choylifatvenezuela/ | accessdate=September 13, 2007 }}</ref> This decision temporarily separated him from his artistic career due to the success he would enjoy as a martial artist.\n\nIn July, 1978, Aguilera earned the [[Black belt (martial arts)|black belt]] in the [[Choy Lay Fut]] [[Kung-Fu]] style,<ref name=\"Certificado 3\">{{cite web|title=La Venciclopedia |work=Julio Aguilera's Black Belt Certificate |url=https://www.venciclopedia.org/index.php?title=Archivo:Certificado_Julio_Aguilera_3.jpg |accessdate=August 3, 2019}}</ref> and during that and the following year he participated in several international competitions and exhibitions, including the [[Muay Thai]] World Championship in [[Manila]], [[Philippines]], the Barehand Championship in China and the International Martial Arts Open of [[Puerto Rico]], which he won in 1979. From that year until 1981, he stayed on the Caribbean island, working as a trainer in [[Santurce, San Juan, Puerto Rico|Santurce]], until he was handpicked to co-develop in [[Venezuela]] ''Top Spa Gym'' at the time the most successful gym in [[Caracas]], located in Las Mercedes sector of the city. Two years later, he was part of the Venezuelan Martial Arts team at the [[1983 Pan American Games]] in the same city.\n\nIn 1983, Aguilera met and married Janice Tuohy, an American choreographer working in the local theater and TV industry. With Touht he opened a multidisciplinary academy with dancing and languages training directed by Touht herself and other [[Venezuela]]n professionals such as [[Anita Vivas]], [[Antonio Drija]] and [[Betty Kaplan]]. The academy didn't last a year and in 1984, Julio and his wife moved to the United States.\n\nAfter a brief stay in [[New York City]], in 1985 Julio moved to [[Diamond Bar]], California, and opened another martial arts academy under the name \"Eagle Lighting\". This time, the business was a success and in a few years he opened other branches in [[Marina del Rey]], [[San Jose, California|San Jos\u00e9]] and [[Sacramento]]. It was while he taught [[Martial Arts]] in [[California]] that he won the Bare Hand [[Kung-Fu]] World Championship in August 1987.<ref name=\"certificado 2\">{{cite web|title=La Venciclopedia |work=Certificado de Julio Aguilera |url=https://www.venciclopedia.org/index.php?title=Archivo:Certificado_Julio_Aguilera_2.jpg |accessdate=August 3, 2019 }}</ref> That same month, he was awarded the 6th [[Dan rank#Modern usage in China|Dan]] in China Kung-Fu, [[I Ching]] [[Kung-Fu]] by the [[International Kung Fu Federation]].<ref name=\"certificado\"/>  Despite all those achievements, Aguilera retired from Martial Arts in 1987, closed down the academies and moved to New York City with his wife. During the following years he flirted with corporate America and the tried opening a few businesses himself, but the Californian success didn't repeat in [[New York City]], where he divorced Janice Touht in 2001.\n\nDuring his years in [[California]], Julio always kept a studio inside the academy, where he painted with lukewarm success. After the several failed business ventures, he began painting professionally around 1997. That year, he bought fifty canvases and in three months developed what is known as the ''Blue Series''.{{Citation needed|date = October 2015}} Aguilera promoted these pieces through web forums and the [[Venezuela]]n Consulate in New York, and by 2000 his work had been exhibited in Spain, [[Argentina]] and [[Venezuela]] in sold out shows.<ref name=\"abn\">{{cite news|title=Art Business News |work=Artist Showcase |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0HMU/is_3_30/ai_98695169 |accessdate=September 13, 2007 |year=2003 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080124234103/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0HMU/is_3_30/ai_98695169 |archivedate=January 24, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"delaware\">{{cite web|title=News of Delaware |work=Venezuelan artist specializes in oil painting |url=http://www.zwire.com/site/news.cfm?BRD=1725&dept_id=498331&newsid=14588517&PAG=461&rfi=9 |accessdate=September 13, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070905160050/http://www.zwire.com/site/news.cfm?brd=1725 |archivedate=September 5, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nAfter a show in the Venezuelan Consulate in 2003,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Paintings by Julio Aguilera and Nino Fernandez Medeglia|url = http://www.absolutearts.com/artsnews/2003/02/14/30755.html|website = www.absolutearts.com|accessdate = 2015-10-27}}</ref> Julio was appointed as the Venezuelan Cultural [[Attach\u00e9]] in New York City, a position he held until 2006. At the same time, he became the General Manager of the [[El Nuevo Cojo|El Nuevo Cojo Ilustrado]] a Hispanic  general interest magazine based in [[Harlem]], and started to experiment with bronze, producing a series of statues from his studio in New Jersey.\n\nAbout his art, critics are uniform about Aguilera's style. He's unashamed about the influence of [[Picasso]] and other Spanish master like [[Goya]], [[El Greco]] and [[Diego Vel\u00e1zquez|Vel\u00e1zquez]]. And according to the art critic Ed McCormack, Managing Editor of Gallery & Studio Magazine, \"''more than any other artist in the Hispanic Diaspora, Aguilera has brought new blood, so to speak, to that still vital tradition, which came to encompass not only the spirit of Spain but all the antique cultural booty that the canny old pirate, Picasso, looted from France Italy and the North.''\"<ref>[https://www.venciclopedia.org/index.php?title=Categor%C3%ADa:Im%C3%A1genes_de_Julio_Aguilera#/media/File:Gallery_y_Studio_febrero-marzo_2007.jpg Julio Aguilera's Passionate Bid for the Mantle of the \"Old Man\"] Ed McCormack. Gallery & Studio, February\u2013March, 2007</ref>\n\n==Recent exhibitions==\n*2019 - Red Dot at Art Basel Miami, Miami, Florida\n*2016 - Art Basel Extension Calle 8, Miami, Florida\n*2016 - Art Basel, Miami, Florida\n*2015 - Afropolis in Gardens Art Basel, Miami Gardens, Florida\n*2015 - Mana Art Basel, Miami, Florida\n*2014 - Mana Art Basel, Miami, Florida\n*2013 - Symposium Sculpture New Art Arcaelogy, Boston, Massachusetts\n*2013 - Symposium Sculpture, Nashua New Hampshire\n*2006 - Davidoff of Geneva. New York City.\n*2005 - Venezuelan Consulate Gallery, New York City.\n*2004 - Citibank Park Avenue. New York City.\n*2004 - Marriott Marquis, New York, New York.\n*2004 - Art. Atlanta. Atlanta Convention Center. Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.\n*2004 - Thyme Gallery, Havertown, Pennsylvania.\n*2004 - Venezuelan Consulate Gallery, New York City.\n*2004 - Art Philadelphia, Philadelphia Convention Center.\n*2004 - International ArtExpo. Jacob Javits Center, New York City.\n*2004 - D\u00e9cor Expo International, Jacob Javits Convention Center New York City.\n*2004 - Citibank. One Rockefeller Plaza, New York City.\n*2003 - Venezuelan Center, New York City.\n*2003 - Frames Works Galleries. Holland, Michigan.\n*2003 - Kandu Galleries. Holland, Michigan.\n*2003 - International Art Expo, Las Vegas, Nevada.\n*2003 - General Motors / GMC. East Hampton, New York.\n*2003 - Art Chicago, - Navy Pier. Chicago, Illinois.\n*2003 - Art Atlanta, - Atlanta Convention Center. Atlanta, GA.\n*2003 - International ArtExpo. Jacob Javits Center New York City.\n*2003 - Galleria West, New Jersey.\n*2003 - Art Miami, Miami, Florida.\n*2003 - Latin Museum. Miami, Florida.\n*2002 - La Gallerie. East Elmhurst, New York.\n*2002 - La Gallery. New York City.\n*2002 - Palm Springs International Art Fair. Convention center Palm Springs, California.\n*2002 - Feria Cuadro Madrid, Spain.\n*2002 - Venezuelan Consulate Gallery. New York City.\n*2001 - International Art Fair. Montreal, Canada.\n*2001 - Venezuelan Consulate Gallery, New York City.\n*2001 - Art Atlanta. Atlanta Convention Center.\n*2001 - Richards. Greenwich, Connecticut.\n*2000 - D\u00e9cor Expo International, Jacob Javits Center. New York City.\n*2000 - Feria Iberoamericana de Arte. Caracas, Venezuela.\n*2000 - ArtBa Feria de Arte Contempor\u00e1neo. Buenos Aires, Argentina.\n*2000 - Venezuelan Consulate Gallery, New York City.\n*1999 - Huntington Public Library, Huntington, New York.\n*1999 - Cosi Public Display. Huntington, New York.\n*1998 - Galleria Portal. Barcelona, Spain.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071230051614/http://www.picassonet.com/julioaguilera/ Picasso net] Gallery with some of Aguilera's work.\n*[http://www.absolutearts.com/artsnews/2003/02/14/30755.html Absolute Arts] Review of exhibit in 2003.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070406224754/http://artareas.com/ArtAreas/home.nsf/ArtistExhibit/JULIO+AGUILERA ArtAreas.com] Gallery with some works of Aguilera.\n*[http://www.wetcanvas.com/forums/showthread.php?t=68031&goto=nextnewest Image from the ''blue series''.]\n*[http://www.wetcanvas.com/forums/showthread.php?t=67986 Image from the ''blue series''.]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aguilera, Julio}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Artists from Caracas]]\n[[Category:Modern artists]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan sculptors]]\n[[Category:Modern sculptors]]\n[[Category:Modern painters]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan painters]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan male martial artists]]\n[[Category:American male martial artists]]\n[[Category:People from Diamond Bar, California]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:20th-century Venezuelan sculptors]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Julio Aguilera by Vicente Saavedra.jpg|220px|right|thumb|''Julio Aguilera'' by Venezuelan painter [[Vicente Saavedra]]]][[Image:Julio Aguilera.jpg|220px|right|thumb|Julio Aguilera during his still hairy Kung Fu days.]][[Image:War and Peace - Julio Aguilera.jpg|220px|right|thumb|''War and Peace''. Bronze, 2004]]'''Julio C\u00e9sar Aguilera Pe\u00f1a''' is a Venezuelan-American painter and sculptor born in [[Caracas]], on July 28, 1961. Previously to his career as an artist, Aguilera was awarded the sixth [[dan rank#Modern usage in China|Dan]] in [[Kung Fu]] when he was just 26 years old.<ref name=\"certificado\">{{cite web|title=La Venciclopedia |work=Certificado de Julio Aguilera |url=https://www.venciclopedia.org/index.php?title=Archivo:Certificado_Julio_Aguilera.jpg |accessdate=August 3, 2019 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nAguilera was born in [[Catia, Caracas|Catia]], one of the poor neighborhoods surrounding [[Caracas]]. His mother died at birth and he was raised by his grandmother and other relatives. At age 6, he was making a living as a shoe polisher while attending primary school. After graduating from high school in 1978 from the Colegio San Agustin, Julio studied at the [[Universidad Pedag\u00f3gica Experimental Libertador|Instituto Pedag\u00f3gico de Caracas]].\n\nAguilera was inclined towards the arts since he was in primary school, and he began painting at a young age after a local painter gave him a handful of used brushes and half-empty tubes of oil paint.<ref>[http://www.artareas.com/ArtAreas/home.nsf/Profiles/JULIO+AGUILERA Julio Aguilera: A Venezuelan Artist Makes His Mark in North America] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070410224514/http://artareas.com/ArtAreas/home.nsf/Profiles/JULIO+AGUILERA |date=2007-04-10 }} Ed McCormack. Gallery & Studio, March, 2005</ref> However strong, his artistic inclinations had to take a back seat for several years while Aguilera struggled to move out of the slums. During this time, he painted mostly for enjoyment, giving away his canvases to friends and relatives while he made his way through school. While at the ''Instituto Pedag\u00f3gico'', Julio enrolled himself in the academy of [[Chan Lee Kam Fai]], one of Venezuela's most renowned martial arts training academies.,<ref name=\"Cham Kam Fai\">{{cite web|title=Hung Sing Choy Lee Fut |work=Maestro Cham Kam Fai |url=http://taichi.cl//index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=14&Itemid=27 |accessdate=September 13, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070822201646/http://www.taichi.cl/ |archivedate=August 22, 2007 }}</ref> unbeknownst Julio, he would later become the future president of the Venezuelan Federation of Chinese Martial Arts and the International Hung Sing Choy Li Fat Chan Kim Fay.<ref name=\"Cham Kam Fai 2\">{{cite web | title=Choy Li Fat Venezuela | work=Historia del estilo Choy Li Fat(C) y Cai Li Fo(M) | url= http://www.angelfire.com/planet/choylifatvenezuela/ | accessdate=September 13, 2007 }}</ref> This decision temporarily separated him from his artistic career due to the success he would enjoy as a martial artist.\n\nIn July, 1978, Aguilera earned the [[Black belt (martial arts)|black belt]] in the [[Choy Lay Fut]] [[Kung-Fu]] style,<ref name=\"Certificado 3\">{{cite web|title=La Venciclopedia |work=Julio Aguilera's Black Belt Certificate |url=https://www.venciclopedia.org/index.php?title=Archivo:Certificado_Julio_Aguilera_3.jpg |accessdate=August 3, 2019}}</ref> and during that and the following year he participated in several international competitions and exhibitions, including the [[Muay Thai]] World Championship in [[Manila]], [[Philippines]], the Barehand Championship in China and the International Martial Arts Open of [[Puerto Rico]], which he won in 1979. From that year until 1981, he stayed on the Caribbean island, working as a trainer in [[Santurce, San Juan, Puerto Rico|Santurce]], until he was handpicked to co-develop in [[Venezuela]] ''Top Spa Gym'' at the time the most successful gym in [[Caracas]], located in Las Mercedes sector of the city. Two years later, he was part of the Venezuelan Martial Arts team at the [[1983 Pan American Games]] in the same city.\n\nIn 1983, Aguilera met and married Janice Tuohy, an American choreographer working in the local theater and TV industry. With Touht he opened a multidisciplinary academy with dancing and languages training directed by Touht herself and other [[Venezuela]]n professionals such as [[Anita Vivas]], [[Antonio Drija]] and [[Betty Kaplan]]. The academy didn't last a year and in 1984, Julio and his wife moved to the United States.\n\nAfter a brief stay in [[New York City]], in 1985 Julio moved to [[Diamond Bar]], California, and opened another martial arts academy under the name \"Eagle Lighting\". This time, the business was a success and in a few years he opened other branches in [[Marina del Rey]], [[San Jose, California|San Jos\u00e9]] and [[Sacramento]]. It was while he taught [[Martial Arts]] in [[California]] that he won the Bare Hand [[Kung-Fu]] World Championship in August 1987.<ref name=\"certificado 2\">{{cite web|title=La Venciclopedia |work=Certificado de Julio Aguilera |url=https://www.venciclopedia.org/index.php?title=Archivo:Certificado_Julio_Aguilera_2.jpg |accessdate=August 3, 2019 }}</ref> That same month, he was awarded the 6th [[Dan rank#Modern usage in China|Dan]] in China Kung-Fu, [[I Ching]] [[Kung-Fu]] by the [[International Kung Fu Federation]].<ref name=\"certificado\"/>  Despite all those achievements, Aguilera retired from Martial Arts in 1987, closed down the academies and moved to New York City with his wife. During the following years he flirted with corporate America and the tried opening a few businesses himself, but the Californian success didn't repeat in [[New York City]], where he divorced Janice Touht in 2001.\n\nDuring his years in [[California]], Julio always kept a studio inside the academy, where he painted with lukewarm success. After the several failed business ventures, he began painting professionally around 1997. That year, he bought fifty canvases and in three months developed what is known as the ''Blue Series''.{{Citation needed|date = October 2015}} Aguilera promoted these pieces through web forums and the [[Venezuela]]n Consulate in New York, and by 2000 his work had been exhibited in Spain, [[Argentina]] and [[Venezuela]] in sold out shows.<ref name=\"abn\">{{cite news|title=Art Business News |work=Artist Showcase |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0HMU/is_3_30/ai_98695169 |accessdate=September 13, 2007 |year=2003 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080124234103/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0HMU/is_3_30/ai_98695169 |archivedate=January 24, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"delaware\">{{cite web|title=News of Delaware |work=Venezuelan artist specializes in oil painting |url=http://www.zwire.com/site/news.cfm?BRD=1725&dept_id=498331&newsid=14588517&PAG=461&rfi=9 |accessdate=September 13, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070905160050/http://www.zwire.com/site/news.cfm?brd=1725 |archivedate=September 5, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nAfter a show in the Venezuelan Consulate in 2003,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Paintings by Julio Aguilera and Nino Fernandez Medeglia|url = http://www.absolutearts.com/artsnews/2003/02/14/30755.html|website = www.absolutearts.com|accessdate = 2015-10-27}}</ref> Julio was appointed as the Venezuelan Cultural [[Attach\u00e9]] in New York City, a position he held until 2006. At the same time, he became the General Manager of the [[El Nuevo Cojo|El Nuevo Cojo Ilustrado]] a Hispanic  general interest magazine based in [[Harlem]], and started to experiment with bronze, producing a series of statues from his studio in New Jersey.\n\nAbout his art, critics are uniform about Aguilera's style. He's unashamed about the influence of [[Picasso]] and other Spanish master like [[Goya]], [[El Greco]] and [[Diego Vel\u00e1zquez|Vel\u00e1zquez]]. And according to the art critic Ed McCormack, Managing Editor of Gallery & Studio Magazine, \"''more than any other artist in the Hispanic Diaspora, Aguilera has brought new blood, so to speak, to that still vital tradition, which came to encompass not only the spirit of Spain but all the antique cultural booty that the canny old pirate, Picasso, looted from France Italy and the North.''\"<ref>[https://www.venciclopedia.org/index.php?title=Archivo:Gallery_y_Studio_febrero-marzo_2007.jpg Julio Aguilera's Passionate Bid for the Mantle of the \"Old Man\"] Ed McCormack. Gallery & Studio, February\u2013March, 2007</ref>\n\n==Recent exhibitions==\n*2019 - Red Dot at Art Basel Miami, Miami, Florida\n*2016 - Art Basel Extension Calle 8, Miami, Florida\n*2016 - Art Basel, Miami, Florida\n*2015 - Afropolis in Gardens Art Basel, Miami Gardens, Florida\n*2015 - Mana Art Basel, Miami, Florida\n*2014 - Mana Art Basel, Miami, Florida\n*2013 - Symposium Sculpture New Art Arcaelogy, Boston, Massachusetts\n*2013 - Symposium Sculpture, Nashua New Hampshire\n*2006 - Davidoff of Geneva. New York City.\n*2005 - Venezuelan Consulate Gallery, New York City.\n*2004 - Citibank Park Avenue. New York City.\n*2004 - Marriott Marquis, New York, New York.\n*2004 - Art. Atlanta. Atlanta Convention Center. Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.\n*2004 - Thyme Gallery, Havertown, Pennsylvania.\n*2004 - Venezuelan Consulate Gallery, New York City.\n*2004 - Art Philadelphia, Philadelphia Convention Center.\n*2004 - International ArtExpo. Jacob Javits Center, New York City.\n*2004 - D\u00e9cor Expo International, Jacob Javits Convention Center New York City.\n*2004 - Citibank. One Rockefeller Plaza, New York City.\n*2003 - Venezuelan Center, New York City.\n*2003 - Frames Works Galleries. Holland, Michigan.\n*2003 - Kandu Galleries. Holland, Michigan.\n*2003 - International Art Expo, Las Vegas, Nevada.\n*2003 - General Motors / GMC. East Hampton, New York.\n*2003 - Art Chicago, - Navy Pier. Chicago, Illinois.\n*2003 - Art Atlanta, - Atlanta Convention Center. Atlanta, GA.\n*2003 - International ArtExpo. Jacob Javits Center New York City.\n*2003 - Galleria West, New Jersey.\n*2003 - Art Miami, Miami, Florida.\n*2003 - Latin Museum. Miami, Florida.\n*2002 - La Gallerie. East Elmhurst, New York.\n*2002 - La Gallery. New York City.\n*2002 - Palm Springs International Art Fair. Convention center Palm Springs, California.\n*2002 - Feria Cuadro Madrid, Spain.\n*2002 - Venezuelan Consulate Gallery. New York City.\n*2001 - International Art Fair. Montreal, Canada.\n*2001 - Venezuelan Consulate Gallery, New York City.\n*2001 - Art Atlanta. Atlanta Convention Center.\n*2001 - Richards. Greenwich, Connecticut.\n*2000 - D\u00e9cor Expo International, Jacob Javits Center. New York City.\n*2000 - Feria Iberoamericana de Arte. Caracas, Venezuela.\n*2000 - ArtBa Feria de Arte Contempor\u00e1neo. Buenos Aires, Argentina.\n*2000 - Venezuelan Consulate Gallery, New York City.\n*1999 - Huntington Public Library, Huntington, New York.\n*1999 - Cosi Public Display. Huntington, New York.\n*1998 - Galleria Portal. Barcelona, Spain.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071230051614/http://www.picassonet.com/julioaguilera/ Picasso net] Gallery with some of Aguilera's work.\n*[http://www.absolutearts.com/artsnews/2003/02/14/30755.html Absolute Arts] Review of exhi